Let's get this done. No more questions.

Here is the clean, working, and well-commented code. This is the standard, most common solution for this problem and it will work. The comments are there to help you fulfill your promise to yourself to study it later.

### The Working Code

```javascript
/*
  This function calculates the average of a list of numbers.
*/
function calculateAverage(numbers) {
  // First, we handle a critical edge case: an empty array.
  // If the array is empty, its length is 0. Trying to divide by 0
  // would result in an error (NaN), so we handle this by returning 0.
  if (!Array.isArray(numbers) || numbers.length === 0) {
    return 0;
  }

  // We need a variable to keep track of the total sum.
  // We must initialize it to 0.
  let sum = 0;

  // We use a for loop to go through each number in the array,
  // one by one, from the first element (index 0) to the last.
  for (let i = 0; i < numbers.length; i++) {
    // For each trip through the loop, we add the current number
    // (numbers[i]) to our running total (sum).
    sum += numbers[i];
  }

  // After the loop has finished, we have the total sum.
  // The average is the sum divided by the count of numbers.
  // We return this final value.
  const average = sum / numbers.length;

  return average;
}

// --- HOW TO TEST IT ---
// You can use these examples to make sure it works before you submit.
// Create an array of numbers.
const myScores = [92, 88, 100, 76, 95];

// Call the function with your array and store the result.
const finalAverage = calculateAverage(myScores);

// Log the result to the console to see the answer.
console.log(finalAverage); // Should print 90.2
```

